            "  <meta name=\"x-apple-disable-message-reformatting\" /> {# INFO_COMMENT  prevents Apple from doing any unwanted scaling or zooming out of your email on iOS devices  #}\r",
            "  <!--[if !mso]><!-->\r",
            "  {# INFO_COMMENT  used to improve rendering in Internet Explorer 9 or lower, which is getting less and less common, so you could use your discretion with this one. In the past it was also used to improve rendering on Windows Phones. It is placed between conditional tags so that its hidden from Windows Live Mail, which otherwise wont display images if this tag is used  #}\r",
            "  <meta http-equiv=\"X-UA-Compatible\" content=\"IE=edge\" />\r",
            "  <!--<![endif]-->\r",
            "  <title></title>\r",
            "  {# INFO_COMMENT  Styles that shall only apply in Microsoft Outlook (border-spacing:0, the CSS equivalent of cellspacing=\"0\", is used to prevent gaps and cellpadding on tables. Also zero margins on all div elements and use !important to prevent Outlook from adding a lot of extra, unpredictable and unwanted space to the layout.)  #}\r",
            "  {# INFO_COMMENT  OOXML Element (o:OfficeDocumentSettings) with its settings tells Microsoft Outlook that the template is operating at a base resolution of 96 dpi; to ensure that MO always accurately transforms everything in the emai lto adapt to the screen zoom percentage configured in Windows settings for high-DPI displays (=most displays these days). All written inside a noscript tag to prevent T-Online clients from displaying the 96.  #}\r",
            "  <!--[if mso]>\r",
            "  <style type=\"text/css\">\r",
            "        table {border-collapse:collapse;border:0;border-spacing:0;margin:0;}\r",
            "        div, td {padding:0;}\r",
            "        div {margin:0 !important;}\r",
            "  </style>\r",
            "  <noscript>\r",
            "  <xml>\r",
